:["onchain_auto/0x0eee3e3828a45f7601d5f54bf49bb01d1a9df5ea/Contract.sol:396","onchain_auto/0x0eee3e3828a45f7601d5f54bf49bb01d1a9df5ea/Contract.sol:1538","onchain_auto/0x0eee3e3828a45f7601d5f54bf49bb01d1a9df5ea/Contract.sol:1552","onchain_auto/0x0eee3e3828a45f7601d5f54bf49bb01d1a9df5ea/Contract.sol:1974","onchain_auto/0x0eee3e3828a45f7601d5f54bf49bb01d1a9df5ea/Contract.sol:1999","onchain_auto/0x0eee3e3828a45f7601d5f54bf49bb01d1a9df5ea/Contract.sol:2285","onchain_auto/0x0eee3e3828a45f7601d5f54bf49bb01d1a9df5ea/Contract.sol:2300"],"claim":"`doTransferIn` only checks whether `transferFrom` returned success; it never compares the contract's pre/post token balance. Supply, repay, and liquidation logic therefore book the requested `amount` as cash received and as user/accounting updates even when a fee-on-transfer, deflationary, rebasing, or otherwise non-standard token causes the protocol to receive less.","impact":"A supplier can receive excess internal credit and later withdraw or borrow against value the protocol never received. Likewise, a borrower or liquidator can repay less than the system records, reducing debt or seizing collateral at a discount and leaving bad debt behind.","paths":["Supplying a transfer-tax token credits `amount` to the supplier and `market.totalSupply` while protocol cash increases by less than `amount`.","Repaying with a transfer-tax token reduces the borrower's debt by the full requested amount even though the market receives less cash.","Liquidating with such a token repays less than recorded but still seizes collateral based on the overstated repayment amount."] ,"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Suspending a borrow market makes solvent positions immediately liquidatable","locations":["onchain_auto/0x0eee3e3828a45f7601d5f54bf49bb01d1a9df5ea/Contract.sol:1315","onchain_auto/0x0eee3e3828a45f7601d5f54bf49bb01d1a9df5ea/Contract.sol:2235","onchain_auto/0x0eee3e3828a45f7601d5f54bf49bb01d1a9df5ea/Contract.sol:2249"],"claim":"When `_suspendMarket` sets `markets[asset].isSupported = false`, `liquidateBorrow` deliberately skips the `discountedRepayToEvenAmount` shortfall-based cap and instead allows liquidation up to the lesser of the user's full borrow and discounted collateral value. There is no requirement that the account actually be undercollateralized once the borrow market is suspended.","impact":"An admin market suspension can immediately expose healthy borrowers in that asset to third-party liquidation and collateral seizure. A risk-management or operational action therefore converts directly into user fund loss.","paths":["A user holds a healthy borrow in `assetBorrow` backed by adequate collateral.","Admin calls `_suspendMarket(assetBorrow)`.","Any third party can then call `liquidateBorrow` against that user and seize discounted collateral even though the account had no shortfall before suspension."] ,"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Oracle price manipulation allows stealing all protocol funds","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Admin-only oracle replacement is an explicit privileged governance power, not a permissionless code flaw or privilege escalation."},{"title":"Unrestricted interest rate model enables rate manipulation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Setting the interest model is an explicit admin control; this is governance trust/centralization, not a standalone vulnerability in the implementation."},{"title":"No maximum cap on origination fee allows 100%+ fees","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is an admin misconfiguration/griefing risk rather than a realistic permissionless exploit or invariant break."},{"title":"All supported markets automatically become collateral","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Market support and collateral admission are both admin-controlled configuration choices; without a separate privilege bypass, this is governance design rather than a code bug."},{"title":"Suspended markets still count for collateral calculations","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This behavior is explicitly documented in `_suspendMarket`; the report does not show an independent exploit beyond the kept finding that suspended borrow markets become liquidatable."},{"title":"No timelock on admin actions allows instant privileged changes","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Lack of a timelock is a governance-centralization concern, not a contract vulnerability by itself."},{"title":"Floating pragma version may cause compatibility issues","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Best-practice concern only; no concrete exploit path or protocol-level harm is shown."},{"title":"Self-destruct possible through admin-controlled equity withdrawal","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`_withdrawEquity` is an explicit admin function limited to protocol equity and does not constitute an unintended exploit path."}]}
