/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic_p5_25_124/foundry_validation/F-001_First_staker_after_a_zero-stake_interval/codex_stderr_attempt5.log:3123:/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic02_p5_25_124/rounds/round_1/merge_stdout.log:1:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Convex extra rewards are claimed to the pool but sold from the RewardManager, permanently stranding them","locations":["0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:76","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:271","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:280","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:399"],"claim":"Convex reward claims send CRV, CVX, and all extra rewards to the Conic pool address via `getReward(_conicPool, true)`, but the liquidation path only checks `IERC20(rewardToken).balanceOf(address(this))` inside `RewardManagerV2`. Because the RewardManager never receives those extra tokens and has no path to pull arbitrary extra rewards from the pool, listed extra reward tokens accumulate in the pool and are never swapped into CNC.","impact":"Any non-CRV/CVX Convex reward stream can become permanently stuck, causing ongoing loss of yield and trapping reward value inside the pool contract.","paths":["Register an extra Convex reward token with `addExtraReward`.","Let a supported Curve position accrue that extra reward on Convex.","Call `claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` or any path that reaches `_claimPoolEarnings()`: Convex sends the extra reward to the Conic pool, but `_swapRewardTokenForWeth()` reads the RewardManager's own balance and swaps nothing."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"The first staker after a zero-staker period can capture all rewards accrued while nobody was staked","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:102","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:106","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:155","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:185","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:178"],"claim":"When `getBalanceForPool(pool)` is zero, `poolCheckpoint()` skips `_updateEarned()` entirely, so `lastHoldings` is not advanced even though CRV, CVX, and CNC continue accruing to the pool. Once any user stakes again, the next checkpoint measures the entire backlog against the new nonzero stake base, and `_accountCheckpoint()` credits that backlog using the user's current staked balance.","impact":"A user can wait until all stakers leave, stake a minimal amount, and appropriate the full accumulated reward backlog. This lets the next staker extract rewards generated by pooled assets during the empty-staking interval.","paths":["All LP stakers exit so `getBalanceForPool(pool) == 0`, while pool assets remain deposited and keep earning Convex and CNC rewards.","During this period, calls to `poolCheckpoint()` do not update `lastHoldings` because the `_totalStaked > 0` branch is skipped.","An attacker becomes the only staker, then triggers `accountCheckpoint()` or `claimEarnings()`, causing the previously untracked backlog to be allocated across the current stake base and captured by the attacker."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"RewardManager pre-books CVX with single-cliff math that can exceed what Convex will actually mint","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:155","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:158","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:104","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:111","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:118","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:120"],"claim":"`poolCheckpoint()` credits users with CVX based on `computeClaimableConvex(claimableCRV)` before any claim occurs. That helper applies one cliff rate to the entire CRV amount, even though actual Convex minting is cliff-dependent and can decrease as a large claim crosses cliff boundaries or as total supply changes before execution. The accounting can therefore book more CVX than the pool will ever receive.","impact":"Users can be credited with more CVX than exists, creating reward-accounting bad debt. Subsequent CVX claims can revert until later accruals backfill the shortfall, causing partial or total denial of service for CVX reward claims.","paths":["Allow a large CRV claim to accumulate, especially near a CVX cliff boundary.","Trigger `poolCheckpoint()` or `claimEarnings()`, which uses `computeClaimableConvex(sumClaimableCRV)` to advance the CVX integral.","Actually claim rewards from Convex and receive less CVX than was pre-booked, leaving `accountShare` totals that exceed the pool's real CVX balance."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Permissionless depeg handling can offboard healthy pools because it relies on a stale price cache","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:558","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:592","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:634"],"claim":"`handleDepeggedCurvePool()` is callable by anyone, but its safety check compares the current oracle price to `_cachedPrices`, which are refreshed only inside `updateWeights()`. If weights are not updated for long enough, normal LP-price drift, oracle updates, or unrelated market movement can push the current price far enough away from the stale snapshot to satisfy `_isDepegged()` even when the Curve pool is still healthy.","impact":"An arbitrary caller may be able to force a healthy Curve pool's target weight to zero, distorting allocations, activating rebalancing rewards, and pushing the pool into unnecessary offboarding and withdrawal flows.","paths":["Let a pool run for a long interval without `updateWeights()`, so the cached price snapshot becomes stale.","Wait until the live oracle price differs from the stale cache by more than `depegThreshold`.","Call `handleDepeggedCurvePool()` and force the pool's target weight to zero despite no genuine depeg event."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Small deposits and withdrawals can revert because allocation rounding leaves no selectable pool","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:233","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:262","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:270","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:392","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:429","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:437"],"claim":"The allocation loops require at least one pool to be strictly underweight for deposits or strictly overweight for withdrawals. For sufficiently small amounts, `targetAllocation_ = totalUnderlying_.mulDown(weight)` rounds to the current allocation for every pool, so `_getDepositPool()` or `_getWithdrawPool()` leaves the selected index at `-1` and reverts.","impact":"Dust-sized operations can become non-depositable or non-withdrawable, causing avoidable denial of service for small users and integrators that assume arbitrary-sized deposits and withdrawals will work.","paths":["Bring the pool close to its target allocation.","Attempt a very small deposit or withdrawal whose size is below the per-pool rounding granularity.","Every pool compares equal to its rounded target, so `_getDepositPool()` or `_getWithdrawPool()` finds no candidate and reverts."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Missing Access Control on handleInvalidConvexPid","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Permissionless access is intentional here and still gated by `isShutdownPid(pid)`, so this is not an authorization bug by itself."},{"title":"Slippage Protection Bypass via Unsupported Tokens","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Under the current reward-claim path, Convex extra rewards are sent to the pool rather than the RewardManager, so the reported unsupported-token swap path is not reachable in normal protocol operation."},{"title":"No Deadline on DEX Swaps","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The Sushi swap already uses `block.timestamp` as a deadline, and the Curve `exchange` interface used here does not expose a separate deadline parameter."},{"title":"Potential Reentrancy via functionDelegateCall","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This depends on a malicious or compromised handler contract configured by trusted governance/controller components; no same-trust-boundary reentrancy path was substantiated."},{"title":"Unchecked Curve Pool Exchange Return Values","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Curve `exchange` returns an amount and reverts on failure; the code is not ignoring a boolean success flag."},{"title":"Division by Zero in ScaledMath.divDown","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a generic library property, not a concrete exploitable protocol issue from the reviewed call sites."},{"title":"Reward Calculation Vulnerable to MEV/Front-Running","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`claimableRewards` is a view function and the report did not establish a permissionless way to reduce pool-held rewards before claims."},{"title":"Lack of Event Emitting for Critical State Changes","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Missing events are an observability issue, not a protocol-impacting vulnerability."},{"title":"Centralization Risk - Owner Has Excessive Privileges","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a governance/trust-model concern rather than a code vulnerability."},{"title":"Insufficient Validation in addCurvePool","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is again an owner-governance quality concern; it does not show a permissionless or unintended exploit path."},{"title":"Missing Zero Address Check in setExtraRewardsCurvePool","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`address(0)` is explicitly supported and means 'do not use a Curve pool', falling back to the Sushi path."},{"title":"Infinite Approval for External Contracts","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a standard trust assumption toward protocol-controlled components, not a standalone vulnerability."},{"title":"Lack of Input Validation in updateWeights","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The reported issue is a policy preference about extreme controller-set weights, not a concrete bug."},{"title":"Potential Integer Overflow in ScaledMath.mulDown","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Solidity 0.8.x already reverts on overflow; no practical overflow exploit was shown."},{"title":"Missing Sanity Checks in withdraw","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Withdrawals are bounded by actual balances and protected by `minUnderlyingReceived`; the report did not demonstrate a silent loss beyond user-accepted slippage."},{"title":"Anyone Can Trigger poolCheckpoint","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`poolCheckpoint()` only updates accounting state and does not transfer rewards to the caller; no theft path was substantiated."},{"title":"Lack of Access Control on setFeePercentage","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The function is `onlyOwner` and capped; this is a governance-policy complaint, not missing access control."},{"title":"Unprotected receive() Function Allows ETH Stuck","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"For non-WETH pools the `receive()` function reverts, so ETH is not silently trapped through the path described."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic_p5_25_124/foundry_validation/F-001_First_staker_after_a_zero-stake_interval/codex_stderr_attempt5.log:3127:/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic_2_p5_25_124/rounds/round_1/merge_stdout.log:1:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"First staker after a zero-stake interval can appropriate the entire uncheckpointed reward backlog","locations":["0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:79","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:101","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:136","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:183"],"claim":"`poolCheckpoint()` computes newly accrued CRV/CVX/CNC from current holdings, but it only advances `earnedIntegral` and `lastHoldings` inside `_updateEarned()`, which is skipped whenever `getBalanceForPool(pool) == 0`. Rewards can therefore keep accruing while no LP tokens are staked without ever being checkpointed. Once any account stakes and later hits `_accountCheckpoint()`/`claimEarnings()`, the entire backlog is divided by the now-nonzero staked supply and can be assigned almost entirely to that first staker.","impact":"A dust staker can capture all rewards that accumulated while the staking supply was zero, extracting CRV, CVX, and CNC value out of the pool’s reward stream with negligible capital.","paths":["All LP stakers leave so `controller.lpTokenStaker().getBalanceForPool(pool)` becomes zero while pool-level rewards continue accruing.","One attacker stakes a minimal amount of LP tokens.","The attacker calls `claimEarnings()` or otherwise triggers `_accountCheckpoint()`.","`poolCheckpoint()` allocates the full previously uncheckpointed backlog against the attacker’s tiny stake, after which the attacker can claim it."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Convex extra rewards are claimed to the pool, but the sale path only swaps RewardManager-held balances","locations":["0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:74","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:76","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:245","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:250","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:309","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:398"],"claim":"Convex claims are executed as `getReward(_conicPool, true)`, so CRV/CVX and all extra reward tokens are delivered to the Conic pool address. However, `_sellRewardTokens()` only inspects `IERC20(rewardToken_).balanceOf(address(this))`, i.e. balances held by `RewardManagerV2` itself. The code never transfers extra reward tokens from the pool into `RewardManagerV2`, and the pool only pre-approves CRV/CVX/CNC to the reward manager. As a result, listed extra reward tokens are never reachable by the swap logic and remain stranded on the pool contract.","impact":"Any Convex extra reward stream configured through `addExtraReward()` becomes permanently unrealizable for stakers, causing lasting loss of protocol yield.","paths":["Governance lists an extra reward token via `addExtraReward()`.","Convex distributes that token during `getReward(_conicPool, true)`, sending it to the pool contract.","`claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` runs `_sellRewardTokens()`, but `_swapRewardTokenForWeth()` sees zero balance on `RewardManagerV2` and does nothing.","The extra reward tokens remain stuck on the pool with no in-scope path to swap or distribute them."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Floor-rounded weight rescaling can leave no valid deposit target while rebalancing is active","locations":["0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:234","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:254","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:263","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:610","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:614","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:618","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:889"],"claim":"`_setWeightToZero()` rescales the surviving weights with `divDown`/`mulDown`, so the post-rescale weights can sum to slightly less than `1e18`. When `rebalancingRewardActive` is true, `_getMaxDeviation()` returns zero, so `_getDepositPool()` only accepts deposits into pools that are still strictly below their exact rounded target. After those rounded targets are filled, any residual deposit amount above the hardcoded 100-unit tolerance has nowhere to go and `_getDepositPool()` reverts with `error retrieving deposit pool`.","impact":"After permissionless emergency weight changes, the pool can enter a state where fresh deposits revert until governance manually resets weights, degrading availability during a stressed rebalancing period.","paths":["A curve pool is zeroed out through `handleDepeggedCurvePool()`, which calls `_setWeightToZero()` and enables `rebalancingRewardActive`.","Floor rounding causes the surviving weights to sum to less than `1e18`.","A later deposit fills every surviving pool up to its exact rounded target while `_getMaxDeviation()` is zero.","If the leftover residue exceeds the 100-unit tolerance, the next `_getDepositPool()` call finds no eligible pool and the deposit reverts."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Standalone reward-token sales can over-credit CNC because sold CNC is added to the integral without syncing `lastHoldings`","locations":["0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:79","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:101","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:136","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:239","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:245","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:252","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:255"],"claim":"`claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` first runs `poolCheckpoint()`, then `_claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` sells extra rewards into CNC and immediately credits `receivedCnc_ / totalStaked` into `_rewardsMeta[_CNC_KEY].earnedIntegral`. That helper does not advance `_rewardsMeta[_CNC_KEY].lastHoldings`, so the sold CNC still appears as fresh `cncEarned` on the next `poolCheckpoint()` and is added to the integral a second time. The user-facing `claimEarnings()` path later resynchronizes `lastHoldings`, so the double count is specifically exposed through the standalone claim/sell path and the fee-triggered internal claim path.","impact":"CNC rewards can be overstated relative to the pool’s actual CNC balance, eventually causing reward insolvency or failed claims for later users.","paths":["Someone calls `claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` directly, or `poolCheckpoint()` internally reaches `_claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` while collecting fees.","Extra reward tokens are sold and the received CNC is added directly to `earnedIntegral`.","`lastHoldings` remains at its pre-sale value.","The next `poolCheckpoint()` counts the same CNC balance delta again and credits it a second time to stakers."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Ineffective Reentrancy Guard Allows Reentrancy Attacks","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The reviewed code does not show a concrete callback path that can reenter `depositFor`/`withdraw` and exploit intermediate state; the end-of-function `reentrancyCheck()` alone is not proof of an exploitable reentrancy bug."},{"title":"Division by Zero in ScaledMath Library","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"A raw division-by-zero revert in a math helper is expected Solidity behavior, and no attacker-controlled in-scope call path was shown that turns this into a distinct protocol vulnerability."},{"title":"Unchecked Return Values from Curve and Uniswap Swaps","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Both swap paths enforce explicit `minAmountOut` values and revert on failure/short output at the external protocol level; not separately inspecting return values does not create the claimed loss path here."},{"title":"Unlimited Token Approvals to External Contracts","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"These approvals are part of the intended trust model toward the configured RewardManager/Convex components, not a standalone vulnerability in the audited code."},{"title":"Unprotected functionDelegateCall to External Handlers","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Delegatecalling controller-selected handler contracts is an explicit architectural trust assumption; this is only exploitable if the trusted controller/handler is already malicious or compromised."},{"title":"Race Condition in Reward Claiming Allows Users to Receive Zero Rewards","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The claim flow is atomic. Another transaction cannot alter balances between the balance check and transfer inside the same execution, and any real insufficiency would revert rather than silently paying zero."},{"title":"Missing Access Control on ConvexHandler Functions","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Direct calls to `ConvexHandlerV3` execute in the handler’s own context and balances. Pool state changes only happen when `ConicEthPool` delegatecalls the handler."},{"title":"Unverified Claimed Amounts from Convex","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Failed external reward claims revert, and balance-delta accounting is the normal way this contract measures claimed CRV/CVX. No concrete exploit path was shown."},{"title":"Exchange Rate Calculation Relies on External Oracles","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a generic oracle-trust observation without a specific manipulation path or code-level flaw unique to this implementation."},{"title":"Lack of Slippage Protection in Deposit/Withdraw","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Deposits and withdrawals already expose user-controlled `minLpReceived` / `minUnderlyingReceived` bounds; the candidate does not show a bypass of those protections."},{"title":"Inconsistent _claimingCNC Flag Creates Edge Cases","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`_claimingCNC` is intentionally used to exclude transient `claimableCnc(pool)` during CNC claims. No separate exploitable inconsistency was substantiated beyond the distinct sold-CNC double-counting bug captured above."},{"title":"Cached Price Can Become Stale","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The cache can certainly age, but this signal was too speculative as written: it did not demonstrate a concrete, realistic false-positive depeg path with measurable protocol harm from the in-scope code alone."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic_p5_25_124/foundry_validation/F-001_First_staker_after_a_zero-stake_interval/codex_stderr_attempt5.log:3205:/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic02_p5_25_124/rounds/round_1/merge_stderr.log:3258:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Convex extra rewards are claimed to the pool but sold from the RewardManager, permanently stranding them","locations":["0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:76","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:271","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:280","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:399"],"claim":"Convex reward claims send CRV, CVX, and all extra rewards to the Conic pool address via `getReward(_conicPool, true)`, but the liquidation path only checks `IERC20(rewardToken).balanceOf(address(this))` inside `RewardManagerV2`. Because the RewardManager never receives those extra tokens and has no path to pull arbitrary extra rewards from the pool, listed extra reward tokens accumulate in the pool and are never swapped into CNC.","impact":"Any non-CRV/CVX Convex reward stream can become permanently stuck, causing ongoing loss of yield and trapping reward value inside the pool contract.","paths":["Register an extra Convex reward token with `addExtraReward`.","Let a supported Curve position accrue that extra reward on Convex.","Call `claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` or any path that reaches `_claimPoolEarnings()`: Convex sends the extra reward to the Conic pool, but `_swapRewardTokenForWeth()` reads the RewardManager's own balance and swaps nothing."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"The first staker after a zero-staker period can capture all rewards accrued while nobody was staked","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:102","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:106","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:155","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:185","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:178"],"claim":"When `getBalanceForPool(pool)` is zero, `poolCheckpoint()` skips `_updateEarned()` entirely, so `lastHoldings` is not advanced even though CRV, CVX, and CNC continue accruing to the pool. Once any user stakes again, the next checkpoint measures the entire backlog against the new nonzero stake base, and `_accountCheckpoint()` credits that backlog using the user's current staked balance.","impact":"A user can wait until all stakers leave, stake a minimal amount, and appropriate the full accumulated reward backlog. This lets the next staker extract rewards generated by pooled assets during the empty-staking interval.","paths":["All LP stakers exit so `getBalanceForPool(pool) == 0`, while pool assets remain deposited and keep earning Convex and CNC rewards.","During this period, calls to `poolCheckpoint()` do not update `lastHoldings` because the `_totalStaked > 0` branch is skipped.","An attacker becomes the only staker, then triggers `accountCheckpoint()` or `claimEarnings()`, causing the previously untracked backlog to be allocated across the current stake base and captured by the attacker."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"RewardManager pre-books CVX with single-cliff math that can exceed what Convex will actually mint","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:155","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:158","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:104","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:111","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:118","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:120"],"claim":"`poolCheckpoint()` credits users with CVX based on `computeClaimableConvex(claimableCRV)` before any claim occurs. That helper applies one cliff rate to the entire CRV amount, even though actual Convex minting is cliff-dependent and can decrease as a large claim crosses cliff boundaries or as total supply changes before execution. The accounting can therefore book more CVX than the pool will ever receive.","impact":"Users can be credited with more CVX than exists, creating reward-accounting bad debt. Subsequent CVX claims can revert until later accruals backfill the shortfall, causing partial or total denial of service for CVX reward claims.","paths":["Allow a large CRV claim to accumulate, especially near a CVX cliff boundary.","Trigger `poolCheckpoint()` or `claimEarnings()`, which uses `computeClaimableConvex(sumClaimableCRV)` to advance the CVX integral.","Actually claim rewards from Convex and receive less CVX than was pre-booked, leaving `accountShare` totals that exceed the pool's real CVX balance."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Permissionless depeg handling can offboard healthy pools because it relies on a stale price cache","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:558","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:592","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:634"],"claim":"`handleDepeggedCurvePool()` is callable by anyone, but its safety check compares the current oracle price to `_cachedPrices`, which are refreshed only inside `updateWeights()`. If weights are not updated for long enough, normal LP-price drift, oracle updates, or unrelated market movement can push the current price far enough away from the stale snapshot to satisfy `_isDepegged()` even when the Curve pool is still healthy.","impact":"An arbitrary caller may be able to force a healthy Curve pool's target weight to zero, distorting allocations, activating rebalancing rewards, and pushing the pool into unnecessary offboarding and withdrawal flows.","paths":["Let a pool run for a long interval without `updateWeights()`, so the cached price snapshot becomes stale.","Wait until the live oracle price differs from the stale cache by more than `depegThreshold`.","Call `handleDepeggedCurvePool()` and force the pool's target weight to zero despite no genuine depeg event."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Small deposits and withdrawals can revert because allocation rounding leaves no selectable pool","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:233","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:262","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:270","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:392","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:429","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:437"],"claim":"The allocation loops require at least one pool to be strictly underweight for deposits or strictly overweight for withdrawals. For sufficiently small amounts, `targetAllocation_ = totalUnderlying_.mulDown(weight)` rounds to the current allocation for every pool, so `_getDepositPool()` or `_getWithdrawPool()` leaves the selected index at `-1` and reverts.","impact":"Dust-sized operations can become non-depositable or non-withdrawable, causing avoidable denial of service for small users and integrators that assume arbitrary-sized deposits and withdrawals will work.","paths":["Bring the pool close to its target allocation.","Attempt a very small deposit or withdrawal whose size is below the per-pool rounding granularity.","Every pool compares equal to its rounded target, so `_getDepositPool()` or `_getWithdrawPool()` finds no candidate and reverts."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Missing Access Control on handleInvalidConvexPid","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Permissionless access is intentional here and still gated by `isShutdownPid(pid)`, so this is not an authorization bug by itself."},{"title":"Slippage Protection Bypass via Unsupported Tokens","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Under the current reward-claim path, Convex extra rewards are sent to the pool rather than the RewardManager, so the reported unsupported-token swap path is not reachable in normal protocol operation."},{"title":"No Deadline on DEX Swaps","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The Sushi swap already uses `block.timestamp` as a deadline, and the Curve `exchange` interface used here does not expose a separate deadline parameter."},{"title":"Potential Reentrancy via functionDelegateCall","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This depends on a malicious or compromised handler contract configured by trusted governance/controller components; no same-trust-boundary reentrancy path was substantiated."},{"title":"Unchecked Curve Pool Exchange Return Values","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Curve `exchange` returns an amount and reverts on failure; the code is not ignoring a boolean success flag."},{"title":"Division by Zero in ScaledMath.divDown","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a generic library property, not a concrete exploitable protocol issue from the reviewed call sites."},{"title":"Reward Calculation Vulnerable to MEV/Front-Running","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`claimableRewards` is a view function and the report did not establish a permissionless way to reduce pool-held rewards before claims."},{"title":"Lack of Event Emitting for Critical State Changes","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Missing events are an observability issue, not a protocol-impacting vulnerability."},{"title":"Centralization Risk - Owner Has Excessive Privileges","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a governance/trust-model concern rather than a code vulnerability."},{"title":"Insufficient Validation in addCurvePool","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is again an owner-governance quality concern; it does not show a permissionless or unintended exploit path."},{"title":"Missing Zero Address Check in setExtraRewardsCurvePool","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`address(0)` is explicitly supported and means 'do not use a Curve pool', falling back to the Sushi path."},{"title":"Infinite Approval for External Contracts","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a standard trust assumption toward protocol-controlled components, not a standalone vulnerability."},{"title":"Lack of Input Validation in updateWeights","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The reported issue is a policy preference about extreme controller-set weights, not a concrete bug."},{"title":"Potential Integer Overflow in ScaledMath.mulDown","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Solidity 0.8.x already reverts on overflow; no practical overflow exploit was shown."},{"title":"Missing Sanity Checks in withdraw","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Withdrawals are bounded by actual balances and protected by `minUnderlyingReceived`; the report did not demonstrate a silent loss beyond user-accepted slippage."},{"title":"Anyone Can Trigger poolCheckpoint","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`poolCheckpoint()` only updates accounting state and does not transfer rewards to the caller; no theft path was substantiated."},{"title":"Lack of Access Control on setFeePercentage","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The function is `onlyOwner` and capped; this is a governance-policy complaint, not missing access control."},{"title":"Unprotected receive() Function Allows ETH Stuck","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"For non-WETH pools the `receive()` function reverts, so ETH is not silently trapped through the path described."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic_p5_25_124/foundry_validation/F-001_First_staker_after_a_zero-stake_interval/codex_stderr_attempt5.log:3305:/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic_2_p5_25_124/rounds/round_1/merge_stderr.log:3068:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"First staker after a zero-stake interval can appropriate the entire uncheckpointed reward backlog","locations":["0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:79","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:101","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:136","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:183"],"claim":"`poolCheckpoint()` computes newly accrued CRV/CVX/CNC from current holdings, but it only advances `earnedIntegral` and `lastHoldings` inside `_updateEarned()`, which is skipped whenever `getBalanceForPool(pool) == 0`. Rewards can therefore keep accruing while no LP tokens are staked without ever being checkpointed. Once any account stakes and later hits `_accountCheckpoint()`/`claimEarnings()`, the entire backlog is divided by the now-nonzero staked supply and can be assigned almost entirely to that first staker.","impact":"A dust staker can capture all rewards that accumulated while the staking supply was zero, extracting CRV, CVX, and CNC value out of the pool’s reward stream with negligible capital.","paths":["All LP stakers leave so `controller.lpTokenStaker().getBalanceForPool(pool)` becomes zero while pool-level rewards continue accruing.","One attacker stakes a minimal amount of LP tokens.","The attacker calls `claimEarnings()` or otherwise triggers `_accountCheckpoint()`.","`poolCheckpoint()` allocates the full previously uncheckpointed backlog against the attacker’s tiny stake, after which the attacker can claim it."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Convex extra rewards are claimed to the pool, but the sale path only swaps RewardManager-held balances","locations":["0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:74","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:76","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:245","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:250","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:309","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:398"],"claim":"Convex claims are executed as `getReward(_conicPool, true)`, so CRV/CVX and all extra reward tokens are delivered to the Conic pool address. However, `_sellRewardTokens()` only inspects `IERC20(rewardToken_).balanceOf(address(this))`, i.e. balances held by `RewardManagerV2` itself. The code never transfers extra reward tokens from the pool into `RewardManagerV2`, and the pool only pre-approves CRV/CVX/CNC to the reward manager. As a result, listed extra reward tokens are never reachable by the swap logic and remain stranded on the pool contract.","impact":"Any Convex extra reward stream configured through `addExtraReward()` becomes permanently unrealizable for stakers, causing lasting loss of protocol yield.","paths":["Governance lists an extra reward token via `addExtraReward()`.","Convex distributes that token during `getReward(_conicPool, true)`, sending it to the pool contract.","`claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` runs `_sellRewardTokens()`, but `_swapRewardTokenForWeth()` sees zero balance on `RewardManagerV2` and does nothing.","The extra reward tokens remain stuck on the pool with no in-scope path to swap or distribute them."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Floor-rounded weight rescaling can leave no valid deposit target while rebalancing is active","locations":["0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:234","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:254","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:263","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:610","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:614","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:618","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/ConicEthPool.sol:889"],"claim":"`_setWeightToZero()` rescales the surviving weights with `divDown`/`mulDown`, so the post-rescale weights can sum to slightly less than `1e18`. When `rebalancingRewardActive` is true, `_getMaxDeviation()` returns zero, so `_getDepositPool()` only accepts deposits into pools that are still strictly below their exact rounded target. After those rounded targets are filled, any residual deposit amount above the hardcoded 100-unit tolerance has nowhere to go and `_getDepositPool()` reverts with `error retrieving deposit pool`.","impact":"After permissionless emergency weight changes, the pool can enter a state where fresh deposits revert until governance manually resets weights, degrading availability during a stressed rebalancing period.","paths":["A curve pool is zeroed out through `handleDepeggedCurvePool()`, which calls `_setWeightToZero()` and enables `rebalancingRewardActive`.","Floor rounding causes the surviving weights to sum to less than `1e18`.","A later deposit fills every surviving pool up to its exact rounded target while `_getMaxDeviation()` is zero.","If the leftover residue exceeds the 100-unit tolerance, the next `_getDepositPool()` call finds no eligible pool and the deposit reverts."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Standalone reward-token sales can over-credit CNC because sold CNC is added to the integral without syncing `lastHoldings`","locations":["0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:79","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:101","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:136","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:239","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:245","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:252","0xbb787d6243a8d450659e09ea6fd82f1c859691e9/RewardManagerV2.sol:255"],"claim":"`claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` first runs `poolCheckpoint()`, then `_claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` sells extra rewards into CNC and immediately credits `receivedCnc_ / totalStaked` into `_rewardsMeta[_CNC_KEY].earnedIntegral`. That helper does not advance `_rewardsMeta[_CNC_KEY].lastHoldings`, so the sold CNC still appears as fresh `cncEarned` on the next `poolCheckpoint()` and is added to the integral a second time. The user-facing `claimEarnings()` path later resynchronizes `lastHoldings`, so the double count is specifically exposed through the standalone claim/sell path and the fee-triggered internal claim path.","impact":"CNC rewards can be overstated relative to the pool’s actual CNC balance, eventually causing reward insolvency or failed claims for later users.","paths":["Someone calls `claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` directly, or `poolCheckpoint()` internally reaches `_claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` while collecting fees.","Extra reward tokens are sold and the received CNC is added directly to `earnedIntegral`.","`lastHoldings` remains at its pre-sale value.","The next `poolCheckpoint()` counts the same CNC balance delta again and credits it a second time to stakers."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Ineffective Reentrancy Guard Allows Reentrancy Attacks","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The reviewed code does not show a concrete callback path that can reenter `depositFor`/`withdraw` and exploit intermediate state; the end-of-function `reentrancyCheck()` alone is not proof of an exploitable reentrancy bug."},{"title":"Division by Zero in ScaledMath Library","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"A raw division-by-zero revert in a math helper is expected Solidity behavior, and no attacker-controlled in-scope call path was shown that turns this into a distinct protocol vulnerability."},{"title":"Unchecked Return Values from Curve and Uniswap Swaps","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Both swap paths enforce explicit `minAmountOut` values and revert on failure/short output at the external protocol level; not separately inspecting return values does not create the claimed loss path here."},{"title":"Unlimited Token Approvals to External Contracts","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"These approvals are part of the intended trust model toward the configured RewardManager/Convex components, not a standalone vulnerability in the audited code."},{"title":"Unprotected functionDelegateCall to External Handlers","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Delegatecalling controller-selected handler contracts is an explicit architectural trust assumption; this is only exploitable if the trusted controller/handler is already malicious or compromised."},{"title":"Race Condition in Reward Claiming Allows Users to Receive Zero Rewards","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The claim flow is atomic. Another transaction cannot alter balances between the balance check and transfer inside the same execution, and any real insufficiency would revert rather than silently paying zero."},{"title":"Missing Access Control on ConvexHandler Functions","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Direct calls to `ConvexHandlerV3` execute in the handler’s own context and balances. Pool state changes only happen when `ConicEthPool` delegatecalls the handler."},{"title":"Unverified Claimed Amounts from Convex","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Failed external reward claims revert, and balance-delta accounting is the normal way this contract measures claimed CRV/CVX. No concrete exploit path was shown."},{"title":"Exchange Rate Calculation Relies on External Oracles","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a generic oracle-trust observation without a specific manipulation path or code-level flaw unique to this implementation."},{"title":"Lack of Slippage Protection in Deposit/Withdraw","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Deposits and withdrawals already expose user-controlled `minLpReceived` / `minUnderlyingReceived` bounds; the candidate does not show a bypass of those protections."},{"title":"Inconsistent _claimingCNC Flag Creates Edge Cases","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`_claimingCNC` is intentionally used to exclude transient `claimableCnc(pool)` during CNC claims. No separate exploitable inconsistency was substantiated beyond the distinct sold-CNC double-counting bug captured above."},{"title":"Cached Price Can Become Stale","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The cache can certainly age, but this signal was too speculative as written: it did not demonstrate a concrete, realistic false-positive depeg path with measurable protocol harm from the in-scope code alone."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic_p5_25_124/foundry_validation/F-001_First_staker_after_a_zero-stake_interval/codex_stderr_attempt5.log:3344:/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic02_p5_25_124/foundry_validation/F-001_Convex_extra_rewards_are_claimed_to_the/codex_stderr_attempt3.log:4156:/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic02_p5_25_124/rounds/round_1/merge_stdout.log:1:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Convex extra rewards are claimed to the pool but sold from the RewardManager, permanently stranding them","locations":["0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:76","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:271","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:280","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:399"],"claim":"Convex reward claims send CRV, CVX, and all extra rewards to the Conic pool address via `getReward(_conicPool, true)`, but the liquidation path only checks `IERC20(rewardToken).balanceOf(address(this))` inside `RewardManagerV2`. Because the RewardManager never receives those extra tokens and has no path to pull arbitrary extra rewards from the pool, listed extra reward tokens accumulate in the pool and are never swapped into CNC.","impact":"Any non-CRV/CVX Convex reward stream can become permanently stuck, causing ongoing loss of yield and trapping reward value inside the pool contract.","paths":["Register an extra Convex reward token with `addExtraReward`.","Let a supported Curve position accrue that extra reward on Convex.","Call `claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` or any path that reaches `_claimPoolEarnings()`: Convex sends the extra reward to the Conic pool, but `_swapRewardTokenForWeth()` reads the RewardManager's own balance and swaps nothing."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"The first staker after a zero-staker period can capture all rewards accrued while nobody was staked","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:102","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:106","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:155","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:185","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:178"],"claim":"When `getBalanceForPool(pool)` is zero, `poolCheckpoint()` skips `_updateEarned()` entirely, so `lastHoldings` is not advanced even though CRV, CVX, and CNC continue accruing to the pool. Once any user stakes again, the next checkpoint measures the entire backlog against the new nonzero stake base, and `_accountCheckpoint()` credits that backlog using the user's current staked balance.","impact":"A user can wait until all stakers leave, stake a minimal amount, and appropriate the full accumulated reward backlog. This lets the next staker extract rewards generated by pooled assets during the empty-staking interval.","paths":["All LP stakers exit so `getBalanceForPool(pool) == 0`, while pool assets remain deposited and keep earning Convex and CNC rewards.","During this period, calls to `poolCheckpoint()` do not update `lastHoldings` because the `_totalStaked > 0` branch is skipped.","An attacker becomes the only staker, then triggers `accountCheckpoint()` or `claimEarnings()`, causing the previously untracked backlog to be allocated across the current stake base and captured by the attacker."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"RewardManager pre-books CVX with single-cliff math that can exceed what Convex will actually mint","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:155","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:158","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:104","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:111","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:118","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:120"],"claim":"`poolCheckpoint()` credits users with CVX based on `computeClaimableConvex(claimableCRV)` before any claim occurs. That helper applies one cliff rate to the entire CRV amount, even though actual Convex minting is cliff-dependent and can decrease as a large claim crosses cliff boundaries or as total supply changes before execution. The accounting can therefore book more CVX than the pool will ever receive.","impact":"Users can be credited with more CVX than exists, creating reward-accounting bad debt. Subsequent CVX claims can revert until later accruals backfill the shortfall, causing partial or total denial of service for CVX reward claims.","paths":["Allow a large CRV claim to accumulate, especially near a CVX cliff boundary.","Trigger `poolCheckpoint()` or `claimEarnings()`, which uses `computeClaimableConvex(sumClaimableCRV)` to advance the CVX integral.","Actually claim rewards from Convex and receive less CVX than was pre-booked, leaving `accountShare` totals that exceed the pool's real CVX balance."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Permissionless depeg handling can offboard healthy pools because it relies on a stale price cache","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:558","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:592","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:634"],"claim":"`handleDepeggedCurvePool()` is callable by anyone, but its safety check compares the current oracle price to `_cachedPrices`, which are refreshed only inside `updateWeights()`. If weights are not updated for long enough, normal LP-price drift, oracle updates, or unrelated market movement can push the current price far enough away from the stale snapshot to satisfy `_isDepegged()` even when the Curve pool is still healthy.","impact":"An arbitrary caller may be able to force a healthy Curve pool's target weight to zero, distorting allocations, activating rebalancing rewards, and pushing the pool into unnecessary offboarding and withdrawal flows.","paths":["Let a pool run for a long interval without `updateWeights()`, so the cached price snapshot becomes stale.","Wait until the live oracle price differs from the stale cache by more than `depegThreshold`.","Call `handleDepeggedCurvePool()` and force the pool's target weight to zero despite no genuine depeg event."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Small deposits and withdrawals can revert because allocation rounding leaves no selectable pool","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:233","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:262","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:270","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:392","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:429","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:437"],"claim":"The allocation loops require at least one pool to be strictly underweight for deposits or strictly overweight for withdrawals. For sufficiently small amounts, `targetAllocation_ = totalUnderlying_.mulDown(weight)` rounds to the current allocation for every pool, so `_getDepositPool()` or `_getWithdrawPool()` leaves the selected index at `-1` and reverts.","impact":"Dust-sized operations can become non-depositable or non-withdrawable, causing avoidable denial of service for small users and integrators that assume arbitrary-sized deposits and withdrawals will work.","paths":["Bring the pool close to its target allocation.","Attempt a very small deposit or withdrawal whose size is below the per-pool rounding granularity.","Every pool compares equal to its rounded target, so `_getDepositPool()` or `_getWithdrawPool()` finds no candidate and reverts."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Missing Access Control on handleInvalidConvexPid","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Permissionless access is intentional here and still gated by `isShutdownPid(pid)`, so this is not an authorization bug by itself."},{"title":"Slippage Protection Bypass via Unsupported Tokens","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Under the current reward-claim path, Convex extra rewards are sent to the pool rather than the RewardManager, so the reported unsupported-token swap path is not reachable in normal protocol operation."},{"title":"No Deadline on DEX Swaps","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The Sushi swap already uses `block.timestamp` as a deadline, and the Curve `exchange` interface used here does not expose a separate deadline parameter."},{"title":"Potential Reentrancy via functionDelegateCall","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This depends on a malicious or compromised handler contract configured by trusted governance/controller components; no same-trust-boundary reentrancy path was substantiated."},{"title":"Unchecked Curve Pool Exchange Return Values","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Curve `exchange` returns an amount and reverts on failure; the code is not ignoring a boolean success flag."},{"title":"Division by Zero in ScaledMath.divDown","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a generic library property, not a concrete exploitable protocol issue from the reviewed call sites."},{"title":"Reward Calculation Vulnerable to MEV/Front-Running","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`claimableRewards` is a view function and the report did not establish a permissionless way to reduce pool-held rewards before claims."},{"title":"Lack of Event Emitting for Critical State Changes","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Missing events are an observability issue, not a protocol-impacting vulnerability."},{"title":"Centralization Risk - Owner Has Excessive Privileges","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a governance/trust-model concern rather than a code vulnerability."},{"title":"Insufficient Validation in addCurvePool","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is again an owner-governance quality concern; it does not show a permissionless or unintended exploit path."},{"title":"Missing Zero Address Check in setExtraRewardsCurvePool","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`address(0)` is explicitly supported and means 'do not use a Curve pool', falling back to the Sushi path."},{"title":"Infinite Approval for External Contracts","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a standard trust assumption toward protocol-controlled components, not a standalone vulnerability."},{"title":"Lack of Input Validation in updateWeights","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The reported issue is a policy preference about extreme controller-set weights, not a concrete bug."},{"title":"Potential Integer Overflow in ScaledMath.mulDown","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Solidity 0.8.x already reverts on overflow; no practical overflow exploit was shown."},{"title":"Missing Sanity Checks in withdraw","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Withdrawals are bounded by actual balances and protected by `minUnderlyingReceived`; the report did not demonstrate a silent loss beyond user-accepted slippage."},{"title":"Anyone Can Trigger poolCheckpoint","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`poolCheckpoint()` only updates accounting state and does not transfer rewards to the caller; no theft path was substantiated."},{"title":"Lack of Access Control on setFeePercentage","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The function is `onlyOwner` and capped; this is a governance-policy complaint, not missing access control."},{"title":"Unprotected receive() Function Allows ETH Stuck","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"For non-WETH pools the `receive()` function reverts, so ETH is not silently trapped through the path described."}]}
/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic_p5_25_124/foundry_validation/F-001_First_staker_after_a_zero-stake_interval/codex_stderr_attempt5.log:3352:/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic02_p5_25_124/foundry_validation/F-001_Convex_extra_rewards_are_claimed_to_the/codex_stderr_attempt3.log:4253:/Users/zhanglongqin/AuditHoundV2/output/conic02_p5_25_124/rounds/round_1/merge_stderr.log:3258:{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Convex extra rewards are claimed to the pool but sold from the RewardManager, permanently stranding them","locations":["0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:76","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:271","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:280","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:399"],"claim":"Convex reward claims send CRV, CVX, and all extra rewards to the Conic pool address via `getReward(_conicPool, true)`, but the liquidation path only checks `IERC20(rewardToken).balanceOf(address(this))` inside `RewardManagerV2`. Because the RewardManager never receives those extra tokens and has no path to pull arbitrary extra rewards from the pool, listed extra reward tokens accumulate in the pool and are never swapped into CNC.","impact":"Any non-CRV/CVX Convex reward stream can become permanently stuck, causing ongoing loss of yield and trapping reward value inside the pool contract.","paths":["Register an extra Convex reward token with `addExtraReward`.","Let a supported Curve position accrue that extra reward on Convex.","Call `claimPoolEarningsAndSellRewardTokens()` or any path that reaches `_claimPoolEarnings()`: Convex sends the extra reward to the Conic pool, but `_swapRewardTokenForWeth()` reads the RewardManager's own balance and swaps nothing."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"The first staker after a zero-staker period can capture all rewards accrued while nobody was staked","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:102","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:106","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:155","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:185","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:178"],"claim":"When `getBalanceForPool(pool)` is zero, `poolCheckpoint()` skips `_updateEarned()` entirely, so `lastHoldings` is not advanced even though CRV, CVX, and CNC continue accruing to the pool. Once any user stakes again, the next checkpoint measures the entire backlog against the new nonzero stake base, and `_accountCheckpoint()` credits that backlog using the user's current staked balance.","impact":"A user can wait until all stakers leave, stake a minimal amount, and appropriate the full accumulated reward backlog. This lets the next staker extract rewards generated by pooled assets during the empty-staking interval.","paths":["All LP stakers exit so `getBalanceForPool(pool) == 0`, while pool assets remain deposited and keep earning Convex and CNC rewards.","During this period, calls to `poolCheckpoint()` do not update `lastHoldings` because the `_totalStaked > 0` branch is skipped.","An attacker becomes the only staker, then triggers `accountCheckpoint()` or `claimEarnings()`, causing the previously untracked backlog to be allocated across the current stake base and captured by the attacker."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"RewardManager pre-books CVX with single-cliff math that can exceed what Convex will actually mint","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:155","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:158","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/RewardManagerV2.sol:104","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:111","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:118","0x635228edaead8a76b6ae1779bd7682043321943d/ConvexHandlerV3.sol:120"],"claim":"`poolCheckpoint()` credits users with CVX based on `computeClaimableConvex(claimableCRV)` before any claim occurs. That helper applies one cliff rate to the entire CRV amount, even though actual Convex minting is cliff-dependent and can decrease as a large claim crosses cliff boundaries or as total supply changes before execution. The accounting can therefore book more CVX than the pool will ever receive.","impact":"Users can be credited with more CVX than exists, creating reward-accounting bad debt. Subsequent CVX claims can revert until later accruals backfill the shortfall, causing partial or total denial of service for CVX reward claims.","paths":["Allow a large CRV claim to accumulate, especially near a CVX cliff boundary.","Trigger `poolCheckpoint()` or `claimEarnings()`, which uses `computeClaimableConvex(sumClaimableCRV)` to advance the CVX integral.","Actually claim rewards from Convex and receive less CVX than was pre-booked, leaving `accountShare` totals that exceed the pool's real CVX balance."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Permissionless depeg handling can offboard healthy pools because it relies on a stale price cache","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:558","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:592","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:634"],"claim":"`handleDepeggedCurvePool()` is callable by anyone, but its safety check compares the current oracle price to `_cachedPrices`, which are refreshed only inside `updateWeights()`. If weights are not updated for long enough, normal LP-price drift, oracle updates, or unrelated market movement can push the current price far enough away from the stale snapshot to satisfy `_isDepegged()` even when the Curve pool is still healthy.","impact":"An arbitrary caller may be able to force a healthy Curve pool's target weight to zero, distorting allocations, activating rebalancing rewards, and pushing the pool into unnecessary offboarding and withdrawal flows.","paths":["Let a pool run for a long interval without `updateWeights()`, so the cached price snapshot becomes stale.","Wait until the live oracle price differs from the stale cache by more than `depegThreshold`.","Call `handleDepeggedCurvePool()` and force the pool's target weight to zero despite no genuine depeg event."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Small deposits and withdrawals can revert because allocation rounding leaves no selectable pool","locations":["0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:233","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:262","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:270","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:392","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:429","0x369cbc5c6f139b1132d3b91b87241b37fc5b971f/ConicPoolV2.sol:437"],"claim":"The allocation loops require at least one pool to be strictly underweight for deposits or strictly overweight for withdrawals. For sufficiently small amounts, `targetAllocation_ = totalUnderlying_.mulDown(weight)` rounds to the current allocation for every pool, so `_getDepositPool()` or `_getWithdrawPool()` leaves the selected index at `-1` and reverts.","impact":"Dust-sized operations can become non-depositable or non-withdrawable, causing avoidable denial of service for small users and integrators that assume arbitrary-sized deposits and withdrawals will work.","paths":["Bring the pool close to its target allocation.","Attempt a very small deposit or withdrawal whose size is below the per-pool rounding granularity.","Every pool compares equal to its rounded target, so `_getDepositPool()` or `_getWithdrawPool()` finds no candidate and reverts."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Missing Access Control on handleInvalidConvexPid","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Permissionless access is intentional here and still gated by `isShutdownPid(pid)`, so this is not an authorization bug by itself."},{"title":"Slippage Protection Bypass via Unsupported Tokens","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Under the current reward-claim path, Convex extra rewards are sent to the pool rather than the RewardManager, so the reported unsupported-token swap path is not reachable in normal protocol operation."},{"title":"No Deadline on DEX Swaps","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The Sushi swap already uses `block.timestamp` as a deadline, and the Curve `exchange` interface used here does not expose a separate deadline parameter."},{"title":"Potential Reentrancy via functionDelegateCall","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This depends on a malicious or compromised handler contract configured by trusted governance/controller components; no same-trust-boundary reentrancy path was substantiated."},{"title":"Unchecked Curve Pool Exchange Return Values","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Curve `exchange` returns an amount and reverts on failure; the code is not ignoring a boolean success flag."},{"title":"Division by Zero in ScaledMath.divDown","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a generic library property, not a concrete exploitable protocol issue from the reviewed call sites."},{"title":"Reward Calculation Vulnerable to MEV/Front-Running","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`claimableRewards` is a view function and the report did not establish a permissionless way to reduce pool-held rewards before claims."},{"title":"Lack of Event Emitting for Critical State Changes","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Missing events are an observability issue, not a protocol-impacting vulnerability."},{"title":"Centralization Risk - Owner Has Excessive Privileges","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a governance/trust-model concern rather than a code vulnerability."},{"title":"Insufficient Validation in addCurvePool","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is again an owner-governance quality concern; it does not show a permissionless or unintended exploit path."},{"title":"Missing Zero Address Check in setExtraRewardsCurvePool","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`address(0)` is explicitly supported and means 'do not use a Curve pool', falling back to the Sushi path."},{"title":"Infinite Approval for External Contracts","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a standard trust assumption toward protocol-controlled components, not a standalone vulnerability."},{"title":"Lack of Input Validation in updateWeights","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The reported issue is a policy preference about extreme controller-set weights, not a concrete bug."},{"title":"Potential Integer Overflow in ScaledMath.mulDown","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Solidity 0.8.x already reverts on overflow; no practical overflow exploit was shown."},{"title":"Missing Sanity Checks in withdraw","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Withdrawals are bounded by actual balances and protected by `minUnderlyingReceived`; the report did not demonstrate a silent loss beyond user-accepted slippage."},{"title":"Anyone Can Trigger poolCheckpoint","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`poolCheckpoint()` only updates accounting state and does not transfer rewards to the caller; no theft path was substantiated."},{"title":"Lack of Access Control on setFeePercentage","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The function is `onlyOwner` and capped; this is a governance-policy complaint, not missing access control."},{"title":"Unprotected receive() Function Allows ETH Stuck","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"For non-WETH pools the `receive()` function reverts, so ETH is not silently trapped through the path described."}]}
